					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10188008#post-4166116</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10188008/scp-3689#post-4166116</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 26 Feb 2019 11:06:53 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>TheMightyMcB</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4483018</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>It can be conceived by anybody who figures out an arbitrary amount of the proper ingredients. Given the sheer spread of stuff that Wery lists as ingredients (and the note that these alone are not enough to come up with the sandwich due to how unrelated they all are) it can be assumed that it isn't exactly hard to expect a drunken frat dude to come up with Kraken's Belly by sheer accident. That uncontainability is why it gets Keter.</p> <p>E: Also, object class is pretty much 100% containment-derived. Nothing to do with danger.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10188008#post-4161152</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10188008/scp-3689#post-4161152</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Fri, 22 Feb 2019 05:10:32 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>CharType</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1711715</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Well, I really like the idea of an infohazardous sandwich, as well as the whole noodle incident of the ingredients. I found it weird that this is Keter though. I reread the object class definition, and it's used correctly, Keter applies to anything that's extremely difficult to contain. Still, it's usually applied to objects that are a threat to human life or the Foundation, and that's what I thought it meant before now.</p> <p>Anyway, I guess I was expecting something more impactful, maybe due to the object class and complexity of the sandwich. I ended up a little disappointed that after all that it just sends the subject on a pirate adventure. No vote for now.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
